  <p> To begin, recall the definition of Linear Equations In Two Variables by clicking here - <xref ref="def-linear-equation-in-two-variables"/>  </p>


<definition xml:id="def-system-of-linear-equations-in-two-variables">
  <statement>
    <p>Two-Variable Linear Systems contain two linear equations with two variables.
      <me>
        \begin{cases}
          A_1 x + B_1 y \amp = C \\
          A_2 x + B_2 y \amp = C 
        \end{cases}
      </me>
      
    </p>
    <p>A solution of a system of equations in two variables is an ordered pair of numbers that is a solution to both equations in the system.
    </p>
  </statement>
</definition>
<example>
  <p>Determine whether <m>(-3,1)</m> is a solution to the system.
    <me> \begin{cases}
          x - y \amp = -4 \\
          x + 5 y \amp = 2 
        \end{cases}
    </me>
  </p>  
<p>To answer this question, we must plug the coordinates <m>(-3,1)</m> into the equations to verify that both equations yield true statements. If one of the equations does not, the ordered pair is not a solution. 
  <me> \begin{cases}
      (-3) - (1) \amp = -4 \amp \implies -4 \amp = -4 \amp TRUE\\
      (-3) + 5 (1) \amp = 2 \amp \implies  2 \amp = 2 \amp TRUE
     \end{cases} 
    </me>
    
</p>
</example>

